-- ============================================================================
-- PENDING / EXPECTED-FAIL — this file documents the NEXT rung, not a regression.
-- ============================================================================
--
-- It lives in not-ok/tc/ because it *should* be rejected, but the check that
-- would reject it does not exist yet. So today it WRONGLY type-checks, and the
-- "parses and checks" golden test reports it as failing (the file succeeds where
-- the not-ok bucket expects a type error). That red is intentional: it is the
-- acceptance test for the next milestone and will turn green once that lands.
--
-- THE NEXT RUNG — party / action-index agreement.
-- The action-type-check fix makes the contract's *declared action type* be
-- enforced (a `DEONTIC P (Action Drinker)` rejects an `Action Eater` value). It
-- does NOT yet relate the two `DEONTIC` parameters to each other: the PARTY here
-- is an `Eater`, the action type is `Action Drinker`, and nothing forces the
-- party's actor to match the action's actor index. That tie — "an actor may only
-- be obligated to do its own actions" — is the dependent / GADT-indexed step.
--
-- WHEN DONE: this clause must be a type error (Eater party vs Drinker action),
-- the "parses and checks" test goes green, and the nlg/schema goldens (which
-- currently capture the wrongly-accepted output) must be regenerated.

DECLARE Eater   IS ONE OF AnEater
DECLARE Drinker IS ONE OF ADrinker

DECLARE Action who HAS `verb` IS A STRING

GIVETH AN Action Drinker
Drink MEANS Action WITH `verb` IS "drink"

-- An Eater party bound to a Drinker action: incoherent, but currently accepted.
GIVETH A DEONTIC Eater (Action Drinker)
`eater bound to drinker action` MEANS PARTY AnEater MUST Drink WITHIN 30
